Dot-Density Example

Jens von Bergmann

2017-08-04

First we install cancensus, grab the newest version just in case. Dont forget to set your API key, refer to the README file for instructions how to get your own.

#library(devtools)
#devtools::install_github('mountainmath/cancensus')
library(cancensus)
#cancensus.set_api_key('your api key')

Load data we want to use for dot density map, use the CensusMapper API tool to select variabes and regions, and we add the format='sp' option to read the data in sp format.

sp <- cancensus.load(format='sp',dataset='CA16', regions='{"CMA":["59933"]}', vectors=c("v_CA16_2066","v_CA16_2060","v_CA16_1916","v_CA16_1727","v_CA16_1937","v_CA16_1958","v_CA16_1973"), level='DA')

For plotting, we also want to plot the aministrative as a base layer for better orientation

# load data for background polygons (geograhic data only)
base_geom <- cancensus.load(format='sp', dataset='CA16', regions='{"CMA":["59933"]}',  level='CSD')
OGR data source with driver: GeoJSON 
Source: "data_cache/CM_geo_6b42dc9bcf266cb7c9bfbbbf40889c49.geojson", layer: "OGRGeoJSON"
with 39 features
It has 11 fields

Next we neet to prepare the data for mapping, we rename the variables and set the colours

sp@data <- sp@data %>% 
  rename(Cantonese="v_CA16_2060: Cantonese",
         Mandarin="v_CA16_2066: Mandarin",
         Punjabi="v_CA16_1916: Punjabi (Panjabi)",
         Farsi="v_CA16_1937: Persian (Farsi)",
         Korean="v_CA16_1973: Korean",
         Tagalog="v_CA16_1727: Tagalog (Pilipino, Filipino)",
         Spanish="v_CA16_1958: Spanish"
         ) 
#categories to map and their colors
categories=c("Cantonese","Mandarin","Punjabi","Farsi","Tagalog","Korean","Spanish")
colors <- c("#ffff66", "#ff3300","#66ff33","#00ffff","#0066ff","#ff66ff","#6600cc")
# 1 dot = <scale> number of people
scale=25

To make the map we have defined a convenience function to handle the dot-density logic. Sparing the details, we need to supply, the data, categories (a vector with the fields we want to map), the colours for each field, a scale (how many people per dot on the map), the base geometry for reference, a map title and map attribution.

All thats left is to call the plot function with our data.

dot_density(geo_data=sp,categories=categories,colors=colors,scale=25,base_geo_data=base_geom,'Most Common Non-Official Languages at Home',attribution="StatCan Census 2016")
Regions defined for each Polygons
